The explanation of their being partly real, partly personal, must be sought in the structure ol their formula in the earlier period. This seems to-have contained two intentiones, the first in rem concepta, and followed by an adiudicatio (‘ quantum adiudicari ex aequo et bono oportet iudex Titio adiudicato’ Gaius iv. 42), the second concepta in personam, 3ηά followed by a condemnatio (e. g. tum quicquid ob eam rem alterutrum alteri dare facere oportet ex fide bona, eius iudex alterum alteri condemnato). Mutatis mutandis, the whole formula was repeated for each of the parties (eg. each joint owner), whence Ulpian calls these actions mixtae in another sense : ‘mixtae actioneS, in quibus uterque actor est¹ Dig. 44. 7. 37. 1. Under Justinian they are in reality in personam only, arising quasi ex contractu, Bk. iii. 27. 3 supr. : ‘finium regundorum actio in personam est, licet pro vindicatione rei est’ Dig. ro. r. 1.
